# ASCII punctuation and complete edits

## Punctuation

- **Curly quotes (enforced):** Use straight double quote `"` and straight single quote `'` (ASCII). Do not use curly/smart quotes (Unicode U+201C, U+201D, U+2018, U+2019) in code, config, or documentation. They are the main cause of search_replace failures when the file has Unicode quotes and your edit uses ASCII.
- **En/em dashes (optional):** You may also use hyphen-minus `-` instead of en dash (U+2013) or em dash (U+2014) for consistency; the script does not check or replace these.
- This keeps search_replace reliable and avoids mismatches when the file already contains Unicode punctuation.
- **Enforcement:** `./scripts/ascii-punctuation.sh check` runs on pre-push and in CI; fix with `./scripts/ascii-punctuation.sh fix`.

## Edits

- **Do not leave broken or half-updated text.** If a search_replace would change only part of a sentence or leave redundant/duplicate phrasing (e.g. "for \"very responsive\" **debounceMs**"), fix the whole span in one go or use Read + Write for the affected section.
- When a replace fails repeatedly (e.g. due to Unicode), do not retry with hex dumps or custom scripts. Prefer: (1) run `./scripts/ascii-punctuation.sh fix` to normalize the file(s), or (2) replace a smaller ASCII-only substring. For files outside the script's scope or if the script cannot run, ask the developer to run the fix script or fix the punctuation manually; avoid Read+Write of very long files (token-heavy).

## For markdown and plan files

See [edit-markdown-plans](edit-markdown-plans.mdc) for targeted strategy (replace boundaries, minimal replace, when to Read+Write).
